issue.title: feat(#1347): `OptimizeMojo` flexible parallelism
issue.body:
I've implemented the issue slightly different comparing with the original puzzle description. I believe that we don't have to "choose" number of thread by hands, `java` can understand how many cores the System has. By that reason it's much easier to use `.parallelStream()` function that creates executor service with number of threads ~= number of cores. Using that method we don't need to use `ExecutorService` directly and set number of threads manually .

Closes: #1347 
___
You can read more about `parallelStream()` [here](https://docs.oracle.com/javase/tutorial/collections/streams/parallelism.html)

issue.title: Choose correct implementation of `TransformerFactory`
issue.body:
When I run `OptimizeMojo` parsing trains in parallel I quite often get the next exception:
```java
Caused by: javax.xml.transform.TransformerConfigurationException: Error checking type of the expression 'funcall(matches, [step("child", 19), literal-expr(^([a-z]+[^><.\[\]()!:"@^$#&/\s]* ?)?[\w\d]+(\.[\w][\w\d_-]*)*$)])'.
```
You can see full log here: 
[trans.log](https://github.com/objectionary/eo/files/10175694/trans.log)

As far as I know, during runtime Java chooses wrong `TransformerFactory` implementation: `com.sun.org.apache.xalan.internal.xsltc.trax.TransformerFactoryImpl` (that supports XSLT 1.0) instead of `net.sf.saxon.TransformerFactoryImpl` (that supports XSLT 2.0). But it happens not often and it's the reason why it is too hard to identify a bug.

The problem has been identified in that [PR](https://github.com/objectionary/eo/pull/1532) and it blocks the PR, actually.
[Failed pipeline](https://github.com/objectionary/eo/actions/runs/3630751877/jobs/6124491950#step:5:1054).

issue.title: feat(#1347): `OptimizeMojo` flexible parallelism
issue.body:
I've implemented the issue slightly different comparing with the original puzzle description. I believe that we don't have to "choose" number of thread by hands, `java` can understand how many cores the System has. By that reason it's much easier to use `.parallelStream()` function that creates executor service with number of threads ~= number of cores. Using that method we don't need to use `ExecutorService` directly and set number of threads manually .

Closes: #1347 
___
You can read more about `parallelStream()` [here](https://docs.oracle.com/javase/tutorial/collections/streams/parallelism.html)

issue.body:
When I run `OptimizeMojo` parsing trains in parallel I quite often get the next exception:
```java
Caused by: javax.xml.transform.TransformerConfigurationException: Error checking type of the expression 'funcall(matches, [step("child", 19), literal-expr(^([a-z]+[^><.\[\]()!:"@^$#&/\s]* ?)?[\w\d]+(\.[\w][\w\d_-]*)*$)])'.
```
You can see full log here: 
[trans.log](https://github.com/objectionary/eo/files/10175694/trans.log)

As far as I know, during runtime Java chooses wrong `TransformerFactory` implementation: `com.sun.org.apache.xalan.internal.xsltc.trax.TransformerFactoryImpl` (that supports XSLT 1.0) instead of `net.sf.saxon.TransformerFactoryImpl` (that supports XSLT 2.0). But it happens not often and it's the reason why it is too hard to identify a bug.

The problem has been identified in that [PR](https://github.com/objectionary/eo/pull/1532) and it blocks the PR, actually.
[Failed pipeline](https://github.com/objectionary/eo/actions/runs/3630751877/jobs/6124491950#step:5:1054).

issue.title: feat(#1347): `OptimizeMojo` flexible parallelism
issue.body:
I've implemented the issue slightly different comparing with the original puzzle description. I believe that we don't have to "choose" number of thread by hands, `java` can understand how many cores the System has. By that reason it's much easier to use `.parallelStream()` function that creates executor service with number of threads ~= number of cores. Using that method we don't need to use `ExecutorService` directly and set number of threads manually .

Closes: #1347 
___
You can read more about `parallelStream()` [here](https://docs.oracle.com/javase/tutorial/collections/streams/parallelism.html)

issue.title: Choose correct implementation of `TransformerFactory`
issue.body:
When I run `OptimizeMojo` parsing trains in parallel I quite often get the next exception:
```java
Caused by: javax.xml.transform.TransformerConfigurationException: Error checking type of the expression 'funcall(matches, [step("child", 19), literal-expr(^([a-z]+[^><.\[\]()!:"@^$#&/\s]* ?)?[\w\d]+(\.[\w][\w\d_-]*)*$)])'.
```
You can see full log here: 
[trans.log](https://github.com/objectionary/eo/files/10175694/trans.log)

As far as I know, during runtime Java chooses wrong `TransformerFactory` implementation: `com.sun.org.apache.xalan.internal.xsltc.trax.TransformerFactoryImpl` (that supports XSLT 1.0) instead of `net.sf.saxon.TransformerFactoryImpl` (that supports XSLT 2.0). But it happens not often and it's the reason why it is too hard to identify a bug.

The problem has been identified in that [PR](https://github.com/objectionary/eo/pull/1532) and it blocks the PR, actually.
[Failed pipeline](https://github.com/objectionary/eo/actions/runs/3630751877/jobs/6124491950#step:5:1054).
